ism       Special Collections and University Archives      Author's Rights      Creative Commons Licenses                      Copyright Questions?     We're here to help!  This guide provides a basic primer about copyright and fair use for instruction.  If you have specific questions, please e-mail copyright@uic.edu.  Disclaimer  These pages were created to provide basic copyright information and are not a substitute for legal advice.                 Copyright is. . .     Protection that is provided by law ( title 17, U.S. Code ) to the authors/creators of “original works of authorship,” including literary, dramatic, musical, artistic and certain other intellectual works.    Copyright laws were created to provide balance and protect the rights of creators and users of copyrighted content.           Rights of the Copyright Owner      Section 106 of the U.S. copyright law grants the owner the exclusive right to:   reproduce the work  prepare derivative works based upon the work  distribute copies of the work to the public by sale or other transfer of ownership, or by rental, lease, or lending  perform the work publicly  display the copyrighted work publicly  in the case of sound recordings, to perform the work publicly by means of digital audio transmission  in the case of a “work of visual art” the author has certain rights of attribution and integrity                 Subject Guide      Sandy DeGroote Email Me           Contact: Professor & Scholarly Communications Librarian 312-413-9494   Subjects: Copyright & Scholarly Publishing                Next: Fair Use >>        Last Updated:  Oct 4, 2019 10:30 AM    URL:  https://researchguides.uic.edu/copyright    Print Page     Staff Login        Subjects:  Biomedical Sciences , Copyright & Scholarly Publishing , Pharmacy , Residency & Fellowships    Tags:  copyright , copyright law , copyright registration , e-learning , fair use , instruction , intellectual property , teaching , title 17                   Logo for the 